  footnotes: []
english:
  title: New Year's Day Below the Gate of Heavenly Eminence
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On New Year's morning, the great palace of Ming opens wide its gates,
    And the robed and crowned of ten thousand lands gather here in ceremony.
    Tigers and leopards guard the threshold, solemn within and without,
    While phoenixes and mandarin ducks divide the ranks, dignified east and west.
    In the cups of birthday wine, the colors of spring drift and float,
    And the guards of the imperial procession stand row upon row in the dawn wind.
    Once I too wore the crimson robe and held the jade tablet among the assembled crowd,
    Yet gazing back at Heaven's Gate, my heart drowns in endless remembrance.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Gate of Heavenly Eminence (Chongtiamen) was the main southern gate of the imperial palace, where New Year ceremonies were traditionally held.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'robed and crowned' refers to tribute-bearing officials and envoys from tributary states attending the imperial court.
  - key: ''
    value: The poet's nostalgia suggests he may have been present at such ceremonies in the past but was now separated from court life, making this poem a meditation on lost position and the passage of time.
